    lastVerifiedAt: "2026-05-08",
    difficulty: "Intermediate",
    body: "Leaving a Michigan or Ohio home for five months in the winter is a calculated risk. The two biggest threats are frozen pipes and break-ins. A pipe that freezes and bursts can dump 250 gallons of water an hour into a closed-up house, and the damage can run into six figures. A break-in at an obviously empty home, with mail piled up on the porch and no lights on at night, can clear out anything of value. The good news is that both threats are manageable with a checklist of preparations done in the weeks before you leave, a few inexpensive devices, and a trusted person who can check on the house once or twice a week while you are gone.\n\nInsurance companies have strict rules about vacant homes. Most homeowner policies require that someone check on the home at least once every 72 hours during the winter, that the temperature be kept above 55 degrees, and that the water be shut off at the main valve if no one is around. Failing to follow the rules can void your coverage, which means that if a pipe bursts on day 90 of your trip, the insurance company can deny the claim entirely. Call your insurance agent before you leave and ask for the vacant home checklist in writing. Some companies sell a snowbird endorsement that loosens the rules in exchange for a small premium increase, which is worth the cost for most retirees.\n\nThe tech side of winter home protection has improved dramatically in the past five years. A $200 smart thermostat from Ecobee or Nest lets you check the temperature from your phone in Florida and adjust the setting if needed. A $30 water shutoff valve from Moen Flo or Phyn can detect a leak and close the main water line automatically. A $100 smart doorbell from Ring or Nest captures who is at the front door and alerts you if a stranger approaches. A $40 smart plug on a living room lamp can turn the light on and off on a schedule, making the home look occupied. Combine the tech with a trusted neighbor or property manager, and you can travel with confidence.\n\nThis guide walks you through the four big preparations: plumbing and HVAC, security and lighting, exterior and mail, and the human side of having a check-in person. Plan to spend two weekends on the full setup the first year. Future winters require only a refresh, since the smart devices and the systems stay in place.",
